x4freetext: Inverse kinematics method
described and preliminary data shown.

x4codes.hlp: Florida State University, Tallahassee, FL, United States of America

x4freetext: A solid polyethylene (C2H4) target of thickness
optimized for the given beam energy in order to stop
incident beam in the target i.e. 1.5  mg/cm2
for 18.5 MeV and 2.5 mg/cm2 for 22 MeV
A set of three annular silicon strip
detectors for the proton recoils, located at 60 degree
were positioned 5 - 7 cm downstream from the
target. The first of three proton detectors was a dE
detector with a thickness of 65 mu-m, the other two
proton detectors and the 7Be detector were 500 mu-m
thick. 7Be detector was located at 24.5 cm from the
target. The time between the events in the proton and
7Be detectors was measured with time resolution of
about 3 ns to eliminate random coincidence background.

x4codes.hlp: Florida State University, Tallahassee, FL, United States of America

x4freetext: The experiment was carried out at the
John D. Fox Superconducting Accelerator Laboratory
at Florida State University.
A radioactive beam of 7Be was produced using
the 1H(7Li,7Be)n reaction. The primary 7Li beam
was accelerated by a 9-MV superFN tandem Van de Graaff
accelerator followed by a linear accelerator booster.
The radioactive nuclear beam facility RESOLUT was used
to separate 7Be from other reaction products and the
primary  detectors and the 7Be recoils in the
downstream S2 detector was then used to identify the
scattering events The composition of the beam was 70%
7Be with 30% 7Li contaminant.
Thick target inverse kinematic method was
used.In this method the heavy ion beam bombards thick
target of lighter nuclei. Target thickness is adjusted
to stop heavy beam ions inside the target.The whole
reaction kinematics is reconstructed from recoiled
light ion, detected outside of the target.
Compiled by S.H.
